1107682507871395840.text: 11/12 Finally, the best way to improve is to watch replays of your own matches and be hypercritical of your decisions. If you want to learn to play or curious about this thread, ask or send a DM.

1107682507158421504.text: 10/12 As the game progresses attention management quickly becomes the most important skill of the group. Players are pulled in unlimited directions. Prioritizing ruthlessly is the only way to win.

1107682506508242951.text: 10/12 Cutting losses is an incredibly useful skill that few people practice regularly and comes with significant cognitive load. The more you do it, the easier it is.

1107682505799450630.text: 9/12 Crisis management is core to success. Learning how to stay calm in high-stress situations and rapidly think clearly about the best outcome of your team is incredibly hard to practice in the real world, as crises are rare.

1107682505220636673.text: 8/12 Scouting (acquiring info) and misdirection in a linear plane are skills rarely practiced and can be applied over and over in life.

1107682504545316864.text: 7/12 Real-time imperfect information requires building intuition and pattern matching at the highest level.

1107682503937146881.text: 6/12 The best players in the world are often playing for the end-game (macro), where their grasp of these skills shine best, but mistakes are amplified and the stakes are higher.

1107682503328960514.text: 5/12 You can build a team or push forward with the team you have, the longer you wait (and more resources acquired), the better your team, but the higher the risk your opponent attacks you and you cannot defend.

1107682502624374785.text: 4/12 Resource management, imperfect information, crisis management & attention distribution are hard to learn in the real world. These skills are played out, in real-time, every match of Starcraft.

1107682501990985729.text: 3/12 A professional player often peaks at 500 actions per minute, that’s ~10 actions/decisions every second. Let that sink in. Mine is somewhere around 200 (and I'm proud of it!)

1107682501378613248.text: 2/12 Context, Starcraft is a stochastic, asymmetrical, unlimited opportunity game often compared to playing 20 games of chess at once, without knowing what your opponent is doing.

1107682500757897216.text: 1/12 The parallels of an advanced Starcraft player and a startup founder are uncanny. I regularly play, stream, and talk about the cognitive benefits of the most stressful hobby I have (for the last 20 yrs).
